INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '58d7f273-c60d-446d-91d2-ddff7f43b88e',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$SvelteKit Loaders Leak Without Abort Signals — Here's the Fix$escape$,
  $escape$SvelteKit's `load` functions receive a `signal` — an `AbortSignal` that fires when the client navigates away or the HTTP connection closes. SvelteKit's built-in `fetch` wrapper honours it automatically, but any native `fetch`, `EventSource`, or `ReadableStream` you open yourself does not.

When you return an unresolved promise from a server `load` (deferred streaming), SvelteKit pipes chunks to the client over an open HTTP connection. If your async generator never checks `signal.aborted`, it keeps producing chunks server-side long after the user has moved on — leaking both memory and open connections.

On the client, `onDestroy` is too late for in-flight requests started after mount. Use `beforeNavigate` instead: it fires before the outgoing route tears down, giving you a clean window to `abort()` any active controllers. `afterNavigate` resets the controller for back-navigation into the same page. Pair this with `onDestroy` as a final safety net for tab-close scenarios.

The pattern: one `AbortController` per page instance, aborted in `beforeNavigate`, reset in `afterNavigate`, and passed as `signal` to every outbound `fetch`.$escape$,
  $escape$<!-- +page.svelte -->
<script lang="ts">
  import { beforeNavigate, afterNavigate } from '$app/navigation';
  import { onDestroy } from 'svelte';

  let controller = new AbortController();

  // beforeNavigate fires before unmount — ideal for aborting in-flight work
  beforeNavigate(() => controller.abort());

  // Reset after back-navigation so the page is usable again
  afterNavigate(() => { controller = new AbortController(); });

  // Final safety net for tab close / component destroy
  onDestroy(() => controller.abort());

  async function loadMore() {
    const res = await fetch('/api/feed/next', { signal: controller.signal });
    if (!res.ok || controller.signal.aborted) return;
    // handle chunks
  }
</script>$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
