INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '24d277b5-0a61-46e2-be80-4eeaea15d3b1',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$SvelteKit API Layer — Route Handlers, Server Actions, and Hooks for Auth$escape$,
  $escape$SvelteKit gives you three distinct tools for server-side logic, and conflating them causes pain.

**`+server.ts` route handlers** are for public API endpoints — think REST or webhook receivers. They export named HTTP method functions (`GET`, `POST`, etc.) and return a `Response`. Use these when external clients need to hit your API.

**Server Actions** (form `actions` in `+page.server.ts`) are for mutations triggered from your own UI. They run on `POST`, integrate with `enhance`, and return typed data back to the page via `ActionData`. No `fetch` needed — SvelteKit wires it automatically.

**`hooks.server.ts`** is where auth lives. The `handle` hook intercepts every request before it reaches a route. Set `event.locals.user` here after validating your session cookie or JWT, then read `locals.user` in any `load` function or action downstream — one validation point, zero repetition.

The golden rule: never do auth inside individual `load` functions. Centralize it in `handle`, guard routes by checking `locals` early, and redirect in the hook itself using `error(401)` or `redirect(303)`.$escape$,
  $escape$// hooks.server.ts
import { redirect } from '@sveltejs/kit';
import { validateSession } from '$lib/server/auth';

export const handle: Handle = async ({ event, resolve }) => {
  const session = event.cookies.get('session');
  event.locals.user = session ? await validateSession(session) : null;

  const protectedRoutes = ['/dashboard', '/settings'];
  const isProtected = protectedRoutes.some(r => event.url.pathname.startsWith(r));

  if (isProtected && !event.locals.user) {
    redirect(303, '/login');
  }

  return resolve(event);
};$escape$,
