INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'a3f75dd6-77af-431d-9b83-f283f0b83098',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$SvelteKit's Automatic Code Splitting — Route Chunks, Dynamic Imports, and Bundle Analysis$escape$,
  $escape$SvelteKit splits your bundle automatically at route boundaries. Every `+page.svelte`, `+layout.svelte`, and `+page.server.ts` becomes its own chunk — Vite handles this without configuration. The client only downloads JavaScript for the routes it actually visits.

For heavy components inside a route, reach for dynamic imports via `{#await import(...)}` or wrap with `svelte:component` after a lazy load. This creates a secondary async chunk, keeping the initial route payload lean.

Server-side modules (`+page.server.ts`, `+server.ts`) are never bundled into the client chunk at all — SvelteKit's module graph analysis strips them entirely, so you get zero leakage of server-only code.

To inspect what ends up in each chunk, run `vite build --mode production` then open `.svelte-kit/output/client/_app/immutable/` — the filenames include content hashes and you can cross-reference with `vite-bundle-visualizer`:

```
npx vite-bundle-visualizer
```

For granular control, use `$app/environment`'s `browser` guard combined with dynamic import to defer third-party libraries (e.g. chart renderers) until after hydration completes, preventing them from blocking the critical path.$escape$,
  $escape$<!-- +page.svelte: lazy-load a heavy chart component after mount -->
<script lang="ts">
  import { browser } from '$app/environment';
  import { onMount } from 'svelte';

  let ChartComponent: typeof import('$lib/Chart.svelte').default | null = null;

  onMount(async () => {
    if (browser) {
      const mod = await import('$lib/Chart.svelte');
      ChartComponent = mod.default;
    }
  });
</script>

{#if ChartComponent}
  <svelte:component this={ChartComponent} data={chartData} />
{:else}
  <p>Loading chart...</p>
{/if}$escape$,
  $escape$typescript$escape$,
