INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '56b133ff-77f5-47fd-817d-9f2506d47a26',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$SvelteKit Production Monitoring — Edge Logs, Sentry in hooks.server.ts, and RUM Web Vitals$escape$,
  $escape$SvelteKit gives you three distinct integration points for production observability, and each requires a different approach.

For server-side Sentry, `hooks.server.ts` is the right seam — wire `handleError` through `Sentry.handleErrorWithSentry()`. This captures errors from both SSR renders and `+server.ts` API routes with full request context via the `RequestEvent`.

Edge functions (routes exporting `export const config = { runtime: 'edge' }`) cannot use the Node.js Sentry SDK. Swap to `@sentry/cloudflare` or `@sentry/vercel-edge` depending on your adapter. `console.log` inside edge routes bypasses Node stdout entirely — output streams to your adapter's log drain (Vercel Log Drains, Cloudflare Logpush), so structure those logs as JSON for queryability.

Web Vitals via RUM require care: the `web-vitals` library only fires on hard navigations by default. In `+layout.svelte`, call your observers inside `afterNavigate` so LCP, CLS, and INP re-register after each client-side route transition. Tag each beacon with `page.route.id` from `$app/state` for per-route dashboards.$escape$,
  $escape$// src/hooks.server.ts
import * as Sentry from '@sentry/sveltekit';

Sentry.init({ dsn: process.env.SENTRY_DSN, tracesSampleRate: 0.1 });

export const handleError = Sentry.handleErrorWithSentry(({ error, event }) => {
  console.error(JSON.stringify({ route: event.route.id, url: event.url.pathname, error }));
});

// src/routes/api/data/+server.ts — edge runtime
export const config = { runtime: 'edge' };

export const GET = async ({ request }) => {
  console.log(JSON.stringify({ ray: request.headers.get('cf-ray'), ts: Date.now() }));
  return new Response('ok');
};$escape$,
